{"author":{"id":"4bb6c1767e50694cfde61856db22bf137d1651e8a0b5ca858c486db3dd02f280"},"ops":[{"type":3,"timestamp":1778732227,"nonce":"NoykfM/sOWA/jKfYuTUPxKleyqE=","message":"Critique of `35f64be` after reading the implementation plan and `0b1f109` comments.\n\nOverall: the plan is pointed at the right decisive experiment. The strongest part is the linear round-trip gate before any GRU interpretation. The main thing I would tighten is that the gate must certify \"same H-infinity game\", not merely \"positive Delta v\".\n\n\nSeveral of the OPEN questions can be resolved now rather than carried into implementation:\n\n- Q1 production plant: resolve as **cs_faithful first, no production training in parallel**. A production-plant Phase 1b is scientifically useful only after the cs_faithful linear round-trip passes. Parallel production training would multiply confounds before the reference game is certified. Cheap production Riccati-only target generation is fine in Phase 0, but not a training arm.\n- Q2 budget shape: integrated rollout L2 should be the primary and only gate budget. Per-step caps are a different adversary class. The class can support them later, but the Phase 3 gate should not mix them.\n- Q3 entry point: `scripts/train_round_trip.py` is the right surface if it reuses library training primitives. Do not force `train_minimax.py` to grow a `cs_faithful` mode if that makes the production CLI harder to reason about.\n- Q4 hold/catch handling: resolve as **hold-free, movement-only** for the round-trip gate. Adding delayed-reach epochs before the linear gate passes changes the game. If GRU wiring needs a go signal, make it a constant/trivial input rather than adding a real hold epoch.\n- Q5 baseline: use both, with different roles. Analytical LQR is the mathematical baseline for the Riccati match; trained warmup-only is the empirical baseline for \"what SGD found without adversary.\" The gate should require consistency with analytical LQR/Hinf, not only warmup-relative Delta v.\n- Q6 budget calibration: default to the Riccati worst-case epsilon trajectory norm at the chosen gamma. The smoke sweep is for numerical stability, not for choosing a scientifically convenient budget.\n- Q7 adversary sharing: per-replicate adversaries are acceptable for training because each replicate is a separate controller. The held-out audit is where \"multiple independent adversaries against the same frozen controller\" belongs. A single shared training adversary across different controllers is not actually cleaner unless all controllers share one trajectory and one policy class.\n\nI would merge Q2+Q6 under \"disturbance metric and budget\" and Q1+Q4+Q5 under \"matched game definition.\" They are not independent decisions.\n\n\nThe ordering is mostly right, but there is a missing Phase 0.5: **analytical target materialization**. Before implementing/training, write out the exact cs_faithful LQR/Hinf trajectories, K_t, gamma*, chosen gamma, worst-case epsilon*, its norm, nominal Delta v, induced gain, and cost time courses. This artifact is the contract the trained linear arm must match.\n\nI would also move \"cost schedule\" out of a standalone Phase 2 and into that target materialization phase. The schedule is not an experimental phase; it is part of the game specification.\n\nThe linear arm should stay before GRU. The GRU arm should not start if any of these fail: K/trajectory mismatch, held-out adversary mismatch, or unclear baseline definition.\n\n\n\"Delta v \u003e +1% with CI overlapping analytical Riccati\" is too loose as the Phase 3 gate. It can pass a controller that is qualitatively not Riccati-like.\n\nI would gate on all of:\n\n- K match: `||K_trained - K_Hinf|| / ||K_Hinf||` below a predeclared tolerance, or explainable deviation in an equivalent policy representation.\n- Nominal trajectory match: peak velocity, time-to-peak, terminal error, and cost time course close to Hinf, not merely positive Delta v.\n- LQR warmup sanity: warmup-only linear controller matches analytical LQR before adversarial training.\n- Robustness match: held-out full-state epsilon loss and/or full-state induced gain close to the analytical Hinf value.\n- Delta v match: within an absolute band around the chosen-gamma analytical Delta v, e.g. +/- 2 percentage points or a predeclared relative tolerance. `\u003e +1%` is a sign sanity check, not a gate.\n- Overshoot fail: the plan already flags `\u003e +30%`; good. I would treat any large positive Delta v with poor K/gain match as failure, not partial success.\n\n\nThe largest technical risk is the phrase \"full-state additive injection on the augmented state.\" In feedbax, `Mechanics` owns plant state, not necessarily the delay-augmented Riccati state. If the cs_faithful analytical state is 48D because of delay augmentation, a post-mechanics intervenor that only mutates effector/plant state will not implement `B_w = I_48`. Conversely, mutating delay-buffer/controller state is a different hook than mutating mechanics state. This needs an explicit state-map before implementation:\n\n`epsilon coordinates -\u003e feedbax StateIndex leaves -\u003e analytical B_w rows`.\n\nWithout that map, the \"matched epsilon\" adversary can silently become another narrower channel.\n\nSecond risk: information structure. The linear regulator being trained must have the same observation/state access as the Riccati controller used for the target. If the Riccati is full-state feedback on an augmented delay state while the trained controller sees a different delayed observation stream, a K mismatch is expected and uninterpretable.\n\nThird risk: epsilon units/metric. A raw Euclidean norm over position, velocity, force/integrator, and lag states is only correct if it matches the Riccati `gamma^2 epsilon^T epsilon` metric. If any state scaling differs between `cs_eq15_cost_schedule`, feedbax state leaves, and the PGD projection, the adversary budget is not the same game.\n\nFourth risk: batch structure. The plan says the same epsilon is applied across the batch. That is fine for a single canonical reach round-trip. It is not fine for mixed reach directions/targets unless the intended game is \"one universal disturbance path across all trials.\" The gate should use a single canonical reach or per-trial epsilon.\n\n\nUsing `cs_eq15_cost_schedule` + `cs_faithful_pointmass` first is the right call. Do not run production plant training in parallel from the start. The first goal is to prove the training pipeline can reproduce a known analytical game. Production plant + movement-ramp is the bridge experiment, not the gate.\n\nI would, however, include a no-training analytical production-plant target in Phase 0.5 if cheap: same report as above, but marked \"not a training gate.\" That gives a bridge without contaminating the decisive test.\n\n\nConceptually sensible, but \"hooking post-mechanics\" is only sensible if this is deliberately a **discrete state update** implementing `x_{t+1} = A x_t + B u_t + epsilon_t`. It should not be described as a force/dynamics perturbation.\n\nImplementation-wise, a normal intervenor component with outputs may not be enough, because it must mutate the `MechanicsState` and possibly delay/augmented-state buffers, not just transform a force signal. I would require a minimal round-trip unit test before training:\n\n- with zero control and a known epsilon basis vector, one simulation step changes exactly the corresponding analytical state coordinate;\n- the empirical linearization recovers `B_w = I_n` for the intended n;\n- delay-state coordinates are either included and tested, or explicitly excluded with the Riccati target rebuilt to match.\n\nThis is a blocker-level design check.\n\n\nThe Phase 4 decision tree should explicitly enumerate the three outcomes from `0b1f109` comment `08b41df`, but tersely. Do not defer that entirely to post-experiment synthesis. Otherwise outcome (a) may be misreported as a plain success when it is actually a human-model mismatch:\n\n- GRU couples gain+speed: full-state epsilon game induces the cs2019 signature even in the RNN.\n- GRU dissociates gain from speed: the RNN is more tracker-like than the human behavioural phenotype; follow-up asks what constraints make humans/regulators couple.\n- GRU partially couples: coupling is quantitative, not binary; report where it lands on robustness-vs-nominal-speed frontier.\n\nThe `0bbd1ef` Path 1 / Path 2 contingency can stay on the synthesis issue, but Phase 4 should point to it explicitly if dissociation occurs. My pushback: architecturally restricting the GRU to force the human signature is a weaker scientific path than adding the minimal biomechanical/plant constraint that removes decoupling. If outcome (a) happens, the next best step is not immediately \"make the GRU match humans\"; it is to identify which real constraint prevents decoupling.\n\nBottom line: keep the plan, but tighten the linear gate into a multi-criterion same-game certificate, resolve most OPEN questions now, and do not implement `FullStateAdditivePerturb` until the exact feedbax-state-to-Riccati-state mapping is specified and regression-tested.\n\nCo-authored-by: Codex (GPT-5) \u003ccodex@openai.com\u003e","files":null}]}